<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>GAUGES AND WARNING LIGHTS - PROGRAMMING - RPM DIP SWITCH</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="program" graphiccount="1">
        <title>RPM DIP SWITCH</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Electronic Engines</title>
            <para>These three DIP switches will be set to one, which programs the Speedo/Tach module to receive data
                link transmissions as input for this function. The signal originates from a Caterpillar, Cummins or
                Detroit Diesel sensor, so there is no further programming needed by service personnel.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Mechanical Engines</title>
            <para>These three DIP switches are used to define engine calibration for rpm. The Speedo/Tach cluster is
                programmed to know the number of pulses from the engine speed sensor per engine revolution.
            </para>
            <para>The DIP switches are located on the top edge of the Speedo/Tach module and can be accessed for
                programming by removing the Speedo/Tach module from the instrument panel.
                <hotlnk document="s08035x_32.xml" xrefid="t0803503">Chart</hotlnk>
                provides the settings for the switches 4, 5, and 6 (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0803511">Figure 11</hotlnk>) for the
                <emph type="bold">RPM</emph>signal.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Switch 7 (tachometer scale) controls the range of RPM readings. Switch 7 is always set at 1
                        for the 0-2500 range. If the tachometer is giving erroneous reads, check this switch setting.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f0803511" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0803511" filename="../figg08/G0803511.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>DIP Switch Settings</caption>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
